// Image List for Chapter 9: Visualizing Cells and Their Molecules

- *Figure 9-1:* A sense of scale between living cells and atoms. Each diagram shows an image magnified by a factor of 10 in an imaginary progression from a thumb, through skin cells, to a ribosome, to a cluster of atoms forming part of one of the many protein molecules in the ribosome.
- *Figure 9-2:* A light microscope. Diagram showing the light path in an upright compound microscope, with condenser, objective, tube, and eyepiece lenses. Also shows a modern upright and inverted research light microscope.
- *Figure 9-3:* Interference between light waves. When two light waves combine in phase, brightness is increased; when out of phase, they cancel each other and brightness is decreased.
- *Figure 9-4:* Images of an edge and of a point of light. Shows interference fringes at an edge and the diffraction-limited image of a point source, illustrating the limit of resolution.
- *Figure 9-5:* Basic principles of light microscopy. The path of light rays through a transparent specimen illustrating the concept of numerical aperture and its relation to the limit of resolution.
- *Figure 9-6:* Contrast in light microscopy. Illustration of (A) bright-field with a stained specimen, (B) dark-field in which scattered light is collected, and (C) phase-contrast in which phase differences are converted to amplitude differences.
- *Figure 9-7:* Four types of light microscopy. Four images of the same fibroblast cell in culture: (A) bright-field, (B) phase-contrast, (C) differential-interference-contrast (DIC), and (D) dark-field microscopy.
- *Figure 9-8:* Making tissue sections. Illustration showing how an embedded tissue is sectioned with a microtome in preparation for examination in the light microscope.
- *Figure 9-9:* Staining of cell components. (A) A salivary gland section stained with hematoxylin and eosin (H&E). (B) A young plant root section stained with safranin and fast green.
- *Figure 9-10:* Fluorescence and the fluorescence microscope. (A) Jablonski diagram showing excitation and emission of a fluorochrome. (B) Excitation and emission spectra for fluorescein (FITC). (C) Diagram of a fluorescence microscope filter set with barrier filters and a dichroic mirror.
- *Figure 9-11:* RNA in situ hybridization. (A) Five different gene expression patterns revealed simultaneously in a Drosophila embryo using fluorescent RNA probes. (B) Individual RNA transcripts detected as single spots in yeast cells.
- *Figure 9-12:* Fluorescent probes. The maximum excitation and emission wavelengths of several commonly used fluorescent probes (DAPI, CFP, GFP, YFP, RFP, FITC, rhodamine, etc.) shown in relation to the visible spectrum.
- *Figure 9-13:* Different fluorescent probes can be visualized in the same cell. A composite micrograph of an epithelial cell with actin filaments in green, mitochondria in red, and the nucleus in blue.
- *Figure 9-14:* Immunofluorescence. (A) Transmission electron micrograph of a cultured epithelial cell periphery showing microtubules. (B) The same area stained with fluorescent antibodies against tubulin using indirect immunocytochemistry.
- *Figure 9-15:* Indirect immunocytochemistry. Diagram showing the principle of signal amplification: many labeled secondary antibodies bind to each unlabeled primary antibody, greatly increasing sensitivity.
- *Figure 9-16:* Green fluorescent protein (GFP). (A) Structure of GFP showing its eleven β-strand barrel. (B) The chromophore buried inside the barrel, formed post-translationally from the side chains of two amino acid residues.
- *Figure 9-17:* Fluorescent proteins as reporter molecules. (A) GFP-labeled neurons in a live Drosophila embryo showing their axons and dendrites. (B) Three different fluorescent proteins used to label individual neurons in different colors (Brainbow technique).
- *Figure 9-18:* GFP-tagged proteins. A cultured mammalian cell expressing EB3-BFP (a plus-end tracking protein) that labels the growing tips of microtubules and can be followed in real time.
- *Figure 9-19:* Fluorescence resonance energy transfer (FRET). Diagram showing how FRET between a blue and a green fluorescent protein fused to two interacting proteins can be used to detect protein–protein interactions inside living cells.
- *Figure 9-20:* Fluorescence recovery after photobleaching (FRAP). (A–C) A fluorescently tagged membrane protein is photobleached in a small region; recovery as unbleached molecules diffuse in is measured to determine mobility and binding kinetics.
- *Figure 9-21:* Visualizing intracellular Ca2+ concentrations using a fluorescent indicator. A false-color image of Ca2+ concentration in a single Purkinje cell from the cerebellum, obtained with the Ca2+-sensitive dye fura-2.
- *Figure 9-22:* Genetically encoded fluorescent biosensors. (A) A FRET-based Ca2+ biosensor using calmodulin flanked by blue and yellow fluorescent proteins. (B) A cAMP biosensor using a FRET pair. (C) The Ca2+ biosensor expressed in an Arabidopsis seedling showing Ca2+ waves.
- *Figure 9-23:* Image deconvolution. (A) A blurred fluorescence micrograph of a C. elegans embryo labeled for microtubules, mitochondria, and DNA. (B) The same focal plane after computational deconvolution, showing a much crisper image with reduced blurring.
- *Figure 9-24:* The confocal fluorescence microscope. Diagram of a laser scanning confocal microscope showing how a pinhole rejects out-of-focus light to produce a sharp optical section at a single defined plane.
- *Figure 9-25:* Confocal fluorescence microscopy produces clear optical sections and three-dimensional data sets. (A) The elaborate cup-shaped trap of the carnivorous plant Utricularia assembled from 452 confocal images. (B) 3D reconstruction of the mitochondrial network in a single yeast cell.
- *Figure 9-26:* Multiphoton imaging. Two-photon infrared excitation allows imaging of active synapses (yellow) on dendritic spines (red) nearly 0.5 mm deep inside a live mouse brain cortex, with changes observed over a day.
- *Figure 9-27:* Structured illumination microscopy (SIM). Illustration of the moiré pattern principle: a known grid pattern combined with the sample pattern reveals higher-spatial-frequency information, improving resolution up to twofold beyond the diffraction limit.
- *Figure 9-28:* Structured illumination microscopy can be used to create three-dimensional data. Three-dimensional projections of meiotic chromosomes in maize at pachytene: (A) conventional fluorescence, (B) 3D-SIM showing resolved lateral elements, (C) color-coded chromosome paths.
- *Figure 9-29:* The point spread function of a lens determines resolution. (A) A point source blurred into an elongated 3D distribution by diffraction. (B) In the focal plane, the distribution is approximately Gaussian with ~200 nm width. (C) Two point sources ~200 nm apart can just be resolved.
- *Figure 9-30:* Superresolution microscopy by reducing the point spread function (STED). (A–C) A torus-shaped depletion laser beam quenches fluorescence everywhere except at the very center, shrinking the effective point spread function to ~20 nm. (D–E) STED images of nuclear pore components showing eightfold symmetry at ~20 nm resolution.
- *Figure 9-31:* Single fluorescent molecules can be located with great accuracy. The mathematical center of the blurred (~200 nm) image of a single fluorescent molecule can be pinpointed to within a nanometer when sufficient photons contribute.
- *Figure 9-32:* Single-molecule localization microscopy (SMLM). (A) Sparse subsets of photoswitchable fluorophores are activated, localized, and bleached in successive cycles; tens of thousands of positions are accumulated into a superresolution map. (B) Microtubules imaged by TIRF (left, ~250 nm) versus PALM (right, ~25 nm) demonstrating dramatic improvement in resolution.
- *Figure 9-33:* Multiple structures below the diffraction limit imaged by SMLM. (A) E. coli cells in a STORM microscope: membrane (green), DNA (blue), and chromosome ends (white dots) at ~20 nm resolution. (B) Periodic actin ring (~190 nm spacing) and spectrin scaffold in a nerve cell axon.
- *Figure 9-34:* Expansion microscopy. (A) Principle: covalently anchor fluorescent labels to a polyelectrolyte gel, digest proteins, then expand the gel up to 10× in water. (B–C) A peroxisome membrane before (blurred) and after 10× expansion, resolving the membrane structure at 25 nm.
- *Figure 9-35:* Expansion microscopy applied to large specimens. (A–B) Top and side views of human nasal epithelial cells expanded 10× showing hollow ciliary basal bodies. (C–D) A 3D segment of mouse brain hypothalamus with six RNA species mapped by sequential in situ hybridization after 2× expansion.
- *Figure 9-36:* Light-sheet microscopy. Diagram showing how a thin sheet of laser light projected perpendicular to the detection axis excites only fluorescent labels in the illuminated plane, enabling rapid, low-phototoxicity, three-dimensional imaging of large specimens.
- *Figure 9-37:* Light-sheet microscopy in the brain. A 1-mm-thick mouse brain section prepared for expansion microscopy and imaged with a light-sheet microscope, allowing tracing of individual pyramidal neurons and all their dendritic connections.
- *Figure 9-38:* TIRF microscopy allows the detection of single fluorescent molecules near the cell surface. (A) Principle of total internal reflection generating an evanescent wave that excites only molecules within ~100 nm of the coverslip surface. (B–C) Formation and endocytosis of an individual clathrin-coated pit tracked over ~10 seconds.
- *Figure 9-39:* The resolution of the electron microscope. A TEM image of a graphene monolayer resolving individual carbon atoms (0.14 nm apart) in a hexagonal lattice, demonstrating near-atomic resolution achievable with modern electron microscopes.
- *Figure 9-40:* The principal features of an inverted light microscope and a transmission electron microscope. Side-by-side comparison highlighting similar optical design: glass lenses in the light microscope versus magnetic coil lenses in the TEM, with the specimen placed in a vacuum for the TEM.
- *Figure 9-41:* Specimen support. A copper or gold grid covered with a thin carbon film that supports the thin sections of a specimen in a transmission electron microscope.
- *Figure 9-42:* Thin section of a cell. A freeze-substituted yeast cell showing the nucleus, mitochondria, cell wall, Golgi stacks, and ribosomes in a state as close to the living condition as possible.
- *Figure 9-43:* Localizing proteins in electron microscopy (immunogold). A protein targeted to the trans-Golgi network is detected by antibodies conjugated to 10-nm colloidal gold particles, appearing as black dots in a thin section.
- *Figure 9-44:* Heavy metals provide contrast in the electron microscope. (A) Platinum-shadowed RecA protein forming a right-handed helix around bacterial DNA. (B) Uranyl-acetate negatively stained actin filaments (~8 nm diameter) showing helical subunit arrangement.
- *Figure 9-45:* The scanning electron microscope (SEM). Diagram showing the SEM principle: a focused electron beam scans the specimen surface, and scattered/emitted electrons are measured to build a high-depth-of-field surface image with 0.5–10 nm resolution.
- *Figure 9-46:* The scanning electron microscope produces surface images with great depth of field. (A) Developing wheat flower spike. (B) Hellebore pollen grains with sculpted cell walls. (C) Chains of bacteria in Stilton cheese veins.
- *Figure 9-47:* Higher-resolution SEM. Macromolecular assemblies shadowed with tungsten and imaged in a field-emission SEM: (A) helical arrangement of actin monomers in a filament; (B) clathrin-coated vesicles.
- *Figure 9-48:* EM tomography. Three-dimensional reconstruction of a complete Golgi apparatus in Chlamydomonas by tilted-view EM tomography, revealing the color-coded cisternal organization and COP1-coated vesicles at ~2 nm resolution by subtomogram averaging.
- *Figure 9-49:* CryoEM structure of microtubules. (A) CryoEM image of microtubules in vitreous ice. (B) Surface lattice reconstruction at 0.35 nm resolution showing protofilament interactions. (C) Electron-density map of the tubulin dimer with α-tubulin (dark green) and β-tubulin (light green) distinguished.
- *Figure 9-50:* The spike protein on the SARS-CoV-2 virus. CryoEM reconstruction of the closed trimeric spike protein from intact frozen virus particles at 0.35 nm resolution, showing receptor-binding domains, heavy N-glycosylation (green), and the viral membrane insertion.
- *Figure 9-51:* Atomic resolution by cryoEM. (A–C) Apoferritin cage imaged by single-particle cryoEM at a record 0.12 nm (1.2 Å) resolution, with clear electron densities around individual hydrogen atoms, rivaling X-ray crystallography.
- *Figure 9-52:* PRC2, a large macromolecular machine. CryoEM structure at 0.35 nm resolution of Polycomb repressive complex 2 (PRC2) with two cofactors bound to a nucleosome, showing the EZH2 subunit directing histone H3 lysine 27 to the methylation active site.
- *Figure 9-53:* Correlated light and electron microscopy (CLEM). Fluorescent IRE1 oligomers in the ER of stressed cells are first localized by light microscopy, then precisely correlated with EM tomography to reveal their concentration in specialized narrow ER tubules.
- *Figure 9-54:* Focused ion beam–scanning electron microscopy (FIB–SEM). Sequential milling of a frozen cell face with a focused gallium ion beam and SEM imaging reconstructs the full cell volume at ~5 nm resolution, correlated with superresolution fluorescence data for the ER and mitochondria.
